        "| **C** | 0.1568 | **0.4229** | **+0.2661** |\n",
        "| **E** | 0.1423 | 0.1660 | +0.0237 |\n",
        "| **A** | -0.0050 | 0.0168 | +0.0218 |\n",
        "| **N** | 0.1081 | 0.0044 | -0.1037 |\n",
        "| **Macro** | **0.0903** | **~0.1700** | **+88%** |\n",
        "\n",
        "### Why did this happen?\n",
        "\n",
        "The improvement comes from **`--few-shot-order balanced`** (now the default):\n",
        "\n",
        "**Old method (`first`)**: Just took the first 5 examples from the workflow in order:\n",
        "1. High C example\n",
        "2. Low C example  \n",
        "3. High O example\n",
        "4. Low O example\n",
        "5. High E example\n",
        "\n",
        "→ Very **heavy on C and O**, almost no coverage of A and N poles.\n",
        "\n",
        "**New method (`balanced`)**: Uses **round-robin high/low selection** across all 5 traits:\n",
        "- O high → O low → C high → C low → E high → E low → A high → A low → N high → N low...\n",
        "\n",
        "This ensures **each trait gets both positive and negative exemplars**, giving the model a much better understanding of the **full range** for each dimension.\n",
        "\n",
        "### Key Insight:\n",
        "\n",
        "**The model learns from contrast.** When you only show it \"high C\" and \"low C\" examples, it gets very good at C, but has no reference for what \"high A\" vs \"low A\" looks like.\n",
        "\n",
        "The balanced selection gives the model **balanced contrast** across all 5 traits, which is why we see the biggest gains in traits that were previously underrepresented.\n",
